title: For Sale:  Glock 27 Gen 3. Lots of extras
postcontent:
I bought it originally to have something smaller to take with me, than my G21, on a 100 mile backpacking trip on the Appalachian trail. I put my decked out G21 on consignment at a local gun shop and when it sold I went in and bought this brand new for a little over 500 dollars which is still what this gen runs new. Buying it new got me a free range coin to use at the range once for free which you can see the little wooden coin in the picture still.

I bought it, took it home, and ordered everything you see in the pictures. Talon grip $18, KKM precision barrel $160, reduced trigger pull kit was $120, tungsten guide rod was $80. and misc titanium pins and extended slide release are on there as well that were a few bucks. When you add it all up, new, its over $900 retail before I even fired the thing. So all the original parts are in the baggy in the pictures brand new.

 The first time i went and fired it I went with a friend who was a member of the range so i got in free, hence why i still have my one time free range coin. I bought a box of winchester white hollow and FMJ rounds. 100 rounds. We had several guns there that day so we shot and I was sure to save ammo for my back packing trip, enough for two full mags. Those same rounds are still in the mag. I havent fired it in 1.5 years since my trip. It just sits around loaded for home defense.

 I understand that all these parts may not be of value to you, i know im not going to get $900 for this gun. But I am in no rush to sell it either. Anyway take a look at the photos and I think you will see its near mint condition. Any way get back at me if you want more photos ill happily oblige.

title: For Sale/Trade:   Custom Gewehr Werks AK74 (AK-105) Rifle
postcontent:
AK47 For Sale or Trade

This is about as custom as it gets in the AK world. The rifle is chambered in 5.45x39. The ergonomics and handling of the rifle are perfect. The sights and longer hand guard allow for better ergonomics and true AR adaptability in an AK. The rifle was parkerized and finished in DuraCoat, which is extremely durable and gives it an authentic looking AK finish. Mag lock-up is nice and stiff with no wobble with a variety of mags. The action is smooth and crisp with zero slop. The rifle comes with one AK74 mil-spec mag as pictured. 

The parts used are the best available all the way through this build. Everything is built around a unused AK-105 barrel assembly, which you can't even find right now from K-var or anyone. The AK-105 barrel length is 12.5' to get the rifle to legal length a Tantal brake has been permanently attached, (pinned and welded). You can Form 4 this rifle no problem and have an nice SBR if you want. The Tantal brake is extremely effective in reducing recoil and muzzle flip. Even with the Tantal brake you can still attach an AK74 bayonet if you have one. Pictured in some of the photos is a Rifle Dynamics AR stock adapter that had some issues. It was swapped with the better and stiffer Canis Stock adapter. I would estimate the round count to be about 400 or 500 rounds tops

This rifle was built by Tim Foreman at Gewehr Werks from a Bulgarian parts kit and the parts listed below. Tim is a perfectionist and does outstanding work and did an amazing job on this rifle. If you’re not familiar with Tim check him out online at http://www.gewehrwerks.com and consider him for your next AK build, you won't be disappointed. 


Parts Breakdown:
Unissued Bulgarian AK74 Kit
New/Unissued AK-105 Barrel Assy.
Texas Weapons Systems -TWS Handguard
TWS Dust Cover
Canis AK-M4 Stock Adapter
Mil-Spec Buffer Assy.
Magpul Mil-Spec CTR Stock
Magpul 1/4' Cheek Riser
Magpul AFG
Magpul MOE AK Grip
Solar Tactical Mag Funnel
Nodak Spud NDS2 Receiver
Krebs Safety 

I work nights so text whenever you want, I turn off my phone when I'm asleep. 
REDACTED

Offering legal documents for sale IS the practice of law and you cannot trust any of the advice they give you because they are not licensed Ohio attorneys.  There must be an attorney-client relationship and consent form filled out.  This is a huge problem and they are putting you and your family at risk by operating against the law.

The Ohio Bar and Supreme Court of Ohio requires that ALL LEGAL advertisements include the attorney's name, address, and phone number.  If you do not see this information in the ad, it is a scam and you should avoid the company at ALL COSTS.  

There are licensed, experience, and qualified attorneys posting here on Armslist.  Look for their information in the ad and call them for your NFA Trust needs.  Do not trust these scam sights which are operating in violation of Ohio law.

NFA Trusts are legal documents that must be individually tailored to your situation, needs, and requirements.  Only a LICENSED and BARRED attorney can do so.  It is against Ohio law for ANYONE to practice law with first being licensed by the Ohio Supreme Court, Bar Admissions.  

Therefore, do not trust this site.  $80 for an entire trust package?  If you take that risk to save a couple bucks, you may well have a document that is not only not legally binding, but can open the door to the ATF confiscating your NFA items for failure to proper operate, create, and run a trust.  

It is a huge risk and I am posting this to warn everyone to stay away.

See the below law for yourself:

http://codes.ohio.gov/orc/4705.07

A) No person who is not licensed to practice law in this state shall do any of the following:

(1) Hold that person out in any manner as an attorney at law;

(2) Represent that person orally or in writing, directly or indirectly, as being authorized to practice law;

(3) Commit any act that is prohibited by the supreme court as being the unauthorized practice of law.

(B)

(1) The use of "lawyer," "attorney at law," "counselor at law," "law," "law office," or other equivalent words by any person who is not licensed to practice law, in connection with that person's own name, or any sign, advertisement, card, letterhead, circular, or other writing, document, or design, the evident purpose of which is to induce others to believe that person to be an attorney, constitutes holding out within the meaning of division (A)(1) of this section.

(2) Only the supreme court may make a determination that any person has committed the unauthorized practice of law in violation of division (A)(3) of this section.

(C)

(1) If necessary to serve the public interest and consistent with the rules of the supreme court, any person who is authorized to bring a claim before the supreme court that alleges the unauthorized practice of law in violation of division (A)(3) of this section may make a motion to the supreme court to seek interim relief prior to the final resolution of the person's claim.

(2) Any person who is damaged by another person who commits a violation of division (A)(3) of this section may commence a civil action to recover actual damages from the person who commits the violation, upon a finding by the supreme court that the other person has committed an act that is prohibited by the supreme court as being the unauthorized practice of law in violation of that division. The court in which that action for damages is commenced is bound by the determination of the supreme court regarding the unauthorized practice of law and shall not make any additional determinations regarding the unauthorized practice of law. The court in which the action for damages is commenced shall consider all of the following in awarding damages to a person under division (C)(2) of this section:

(a) The extent to which the fee paid for the services that constitute the unauthorized practice of law in violation of division (A)(3) of this section exceeds the reasonable fees charged by licensed attorneys in the area in which the violation occurred;

(b) The costs incurred in paying for legal advice to correct any inadequacies in the services that constitute the unauthorized practice of law in violation of division (A)(3) of this section;

(c) Any other damages proximately caused by the failure of the person performing the services that constitute the unauthorized practice of law to have the license to practice law in this state that is required to perform the services;

(d) Any reasonable attorney's fees that are incurred in bringing the civil action under division (C)(1) or (2) of this section.

(3) Divisions (C)(1) and (2) of this section apply, and may be utilized, only regarding acts that are the unauthorized practice of law in violation of division (A)(3) of this section and that occur on or after the effective date of this amendment.

Effective Date: 09-30-1997; 09-15-2004
